The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Pfizer boss quits

 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT 

 Mumbai, March 9: Pfizer managing director Hocine Sidi Said today announced his plans to quit the company to explore other options. A company spokesperson said Said was leaving Pfizer and India. She did not offer details on his successor.

 Said spent four years in India as managing director and over 19 years with the parent company, Pfizer Inc. During his stint with Pfizer, he has been country manager in Denmark, Egypt and Indonesia. In India, he was in charge of the mergers with Parke-Davis (India) and Pharmacia. 

 Pfizer?s net profit jumped 125 per cent to Rs 13.71 crore for the quarter ended November 30 against Rs 6.10 crore in the corresponding period last year. 

 Total income during the quarter increased modestly to Rs 149.32 crore against Rs 143.75 crore in the same period last year.

 The amalgamation of Pharmacia Healthcare with the company was approved by Bombay High Court by its order on February 4. For the year ended November 30, the company posted a net profit of Rs 45.52 crore compared with Rs 27.51 crore in the previous year. Total income was at Rs 597.02 crore over Rs 515.16 crore. On BSE today, Pfizer shares opened at Rs 695.85, rose to an intra-day high of Rs 719.90 and closed at Rs 714.55. 




